explanation:
OS_CHECK_POINTER - This is a macro invoked directly in the target function; its expansion may introduce controlling expressions (if/return/loop). To check MISRA R-14.4 (invariant controlling expressions) you must inspect the macro body.

OS_printf - Often used inside pointer-check macros to report errors. If OS_CHECK_POINTER calls OS_printf, any conditional around that call or within its macro expansion must be examined for invariant control expressions.

LOCAL_OBJID_TYPE - The constant/macro used as the first argument to OS_ObjectIdFindByName. If this is a macro or enum that expands to an expression, it should be checked (macros can hide control constructs or constant expressions).

OS_ObjectIdFindByName - Although a normal function call, if it is implemented as a static/inline function or macro in the same translation unit its body could introduce controlling expressions that effectively become part of the calling function when inlined/expanded. Confirming its definition ensures no hidden invariant controlling expressions are being introduced into the callers' effective control flow.

osal_id_t - The type of sem_id (and possibly its qualifiers). If OS_CHECK_POINTER or other macros rely on type-specific behaviour (e.g. casts, compile-time constant checks) the type definition can affect macro expansion and any compile-time constant expressions.

UT_Stub_RegisterReturnType, UT_Stub_RegisterContextWithMetaData, UT_ExecuteBasicHandler, UT_Stub_GetReturnValuePtr - The static call graph shows the target function may invoke unit-test stub instrumentation (these symbols). Some test macros expand into calls/conditionals that are present in the function body after preprocessing; their expansions can contain control statements. Include them so the next analyser can inspect whether any of these test-hook expansions introduce invariant controlling expressions.
